<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1358,193,218]" box="[192,1358,193,218]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,372,193,217]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only in the 
<collectingCountry box="[613,784,194,218]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">United States</collectingCountry>
in the southwestern state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1143,1240,194,218]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Arizona</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1256,1345,194,218]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="26.[192,275,1662,1684]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-27@26.[192,1440,192,1643]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figure 34. Western North American distribution of Anogdus fusciclavus (squares), A. insolitus (inverted triangles), A. sculpturatus (crosses), A. cochise (triangles), A. huachuca (circles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5175809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5175809/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1095,257,282]" box="[192,1095,257,282]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,360,257,281]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults are known only from the month of July and August.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1196,321,346]" box="[192,1196,321,346]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,345,321,345]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Bionomics.</emphasis>
The presumed habitat is seasonal mixed forest in protected canyons.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1440,386,442]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,348,386,410]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
